<br>
a: your raid puller is inadequate.<br>
<br>
b: your raid puller quits.<br>
<br>
c: your raid puller wants a break.<br>
<br>
The problem with moving into a raid puller position immediately is that your raids will be slowing down.  Your best bet in a scenario like this is to talk to the puller and offer assistance pulling.  That way you get to know the pulls, get to watch your puller, and get to see the in's and out's of raid pulling.  <br>
<br>
Before any bard starts pulling I'd make sure you're max FT, max defensive aa, and high MR. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;font-size:xx-small;"><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=74894" target="top">Muse Gwenwyvar the Maestro</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
